<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="179" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,757,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,865,892]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognized among other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1840" box="[743,843,866,892]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[743,843,866,892]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Acalypta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a combination of the following characters: body dark gray, elongate in brachypterous morph and oblong in macropterous morph, approximately 
<quantity box="[1230,1317,902,929]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
long from head to apices of hemelytra in brachypterous morph and approximately 
<quantity box="[955,1041,938,965]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.9 mm</quantity>
long in macropterous morph (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
A–B, 1E–F); antenniferous tubercles sharp and straight; pronotum tricarinate, 1.2 times as long as maximum width across paranota; calli coarsely punctate; paranotum with 3 rows of areolae at widest part; anterolateral angle of paranotum angular, strongly protruding anteriad, reaching mid-level of compound eye; posterolateral angle of paranotum not protruding posteriad; posterior process of pronotum long, 1.2 times as wide as its length; posterior margin of hemelytron in brachypterous morph weakly sinuate (
<figureCitation box="[851,939,1118,1144]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
); gap between both hemelytra in brachypterous morph narrower than discoidal area at each widest part (
<figureCitation box="[826,908,1154,1180]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Fig 1A</figureCitation>
); costal area with 2 rows of areolae throughout its length; subcostal area with 3 rows of areolae at its widest part; discoidal area in both brachypterous and macropterous morphs not expanded beyond apical fourth of hemelytron, as wide as subcostal area at widest parts of each; basal third of discoidal-sutural boundary vein strongly carinate; pygophore flat and pentagonal, triangularly elevated at center of venter, arranged with several distinct transverse wrinkles (
<figureCitation box="[932,1032,1298,1324]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,971,996]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,170,960]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,170,960]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. A–D. Apical part of abdomen, ventral view. A. cooleyi, male (A) and female (C); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., male (B) and female (D). Scale bars: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150313/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Figs. 2A</figureCitation>
, 3A); apical margin of female abdomen rounded, weakly concave at apex (
<figureCitation box="[594,683,1334,1360]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,971,996]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,170,960]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,170,960]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. A–D. Apical part of abdomen, ventral view. A. cooleyi, male (A) and female (C); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., male (B) and female (D). Scale bars: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150313/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
); and paramere thick and long, evenly curved inward (Fig. 3C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="179" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,757,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1370,1396]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species slightly resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fieber, 1844)" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1844" baseAuthorityName="Fieber" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[686,978,1370,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[686,703,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[719,805,1370,1396]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">gracilis</emphasis>
(Fieber, 1844)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Torre-Bueno, 1916" authorityName="Torre-Bueno" authorityYear="1916" box="[991,1336,1370,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lillianis">
<emphasis box="[991,1008,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1024,1110,1370,1396]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">lillianis</emphasis>
Torre-Bueno, 1916
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wolff, 1804)" authorityName="Wolff" authorityYear="1804" baseAuthorityName="Wolff" baseAuthorityYear="1804" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[1349,1366,1371,1397]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">marginata</emphasis>
(Wolff, 1804)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fallen, 1807)" authorityName="Fallen" authorityYear="1807" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1807" box="[402,691,1406,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvula">
<emphasis box="[402,419,1407,1433]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[435,522,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">parvula</emphasis>
(Fallén, 1807)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fieber, 1844)" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1844" baseAuthorityName="Fieber" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[749,1076,1406,1433]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="platycheila">
<emphasis box="[749,766,1407,1433]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[782,906,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">platycheila</emphasis>
(Fieber, 1844)
</taxonomicName>
in general appearance, but it is easily distinguished from them by the following characters: antenniferous tubercles sharp and straight (
<figureCitation box="[1290,1362,1442,1468]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
A–B); anterolateral angle of paranotum angular, strongly protruding anteriad, reaching mid-level of compound eye (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
A–B). It is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Jakovlev, 1880)" authorityName="Jakovlev" authorityYear="1880" baseAuthorityName="Jakovlev" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[466,818,1514,1541]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutangula">
<emphasis box="[466,483,1515,1541]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[497,623,1514,1540]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">acutangula</emphasis>
(Jakovlev, 1880)
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of the antenniferous tubercles and the anterolateral angle of the paranotum, but it can be distinguished from the latter by the following characters: posterior margin of hemelytron in brachypterous morph weakly sinuate (
<figureCitation box="[878,969,1586,1612]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
); the gap between both hemelytra of the brachypterous morph narrower than discoidal area at widest part of each (
<figureCitation box="[979,1069,1622,1648]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
); and subcostal area with 3 rows of areolae at its widest part (
<figureCitation box="[468,542,1658,1684]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1184,1209]" captionTargetBox="[156,1427,176,1166]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,174,1172]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–H. Habitus of Acalypta species from Japan, dorsal and lateral view. A. cooleyi, brachypterous male (A, E) and macropterous female (B, F); A. pallidicoronata sp. nov., brachypterous male (C, G) and female (D, H). Scale bars: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3150307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
A–B). On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Jakovlev" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[837,994,1658,1685]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acutangula">
<emphasis box="[837,854,1659,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[868,994,1658,1684]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">acutangula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the posterior margin of hemelytron strongly sinuate in the brachypterous morph; the gap between both hemelytra of the brachypterous morph wider than discoidal area at widest part of each; and subcostal area with 4–5 rows of areolae at its widest part.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,757,2009]" box="[199,1142,1766,1793]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">
A tingid recorded as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1840" box="[432,532,1766,1792]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[432,532,1766,1792]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Acalypta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. by 
<bibRefCitation author="Maehara, S." box="[613,793,1766,1792]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="57 - 64" refId="ref4127" refString="Maehara, S. (2014) [Tingidae from Tochigi-ken, Honshu, Japan]. Insekuto, 65 (1), 57 - 64. [in Japanese]" type="journal article" year="2014">Maehara (2014)</bibRefCitation>
also corresponds to 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Drake &amp; Lattin" authorityYear="1963" box="[1023,1135,1766,1793]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Acalypta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cooleyi">
<emphasis box="[1023,1040,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1054,1135,1766,1792]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">cooleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="179" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,757,2009]" box="[199,1376,1801,1829]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1801,1828]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,423,1803,1829]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Japan</collectingCountry>
(Honshu), northern 
<collectingCountry box="[652,722,1802,1828]" name="China" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">China</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[733,867,1802,1828]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[877,989,1802,1828]" name="Mongolia" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1087,1164,1802,1828]" name="Russia" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Russia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1175,1288,1802,1828]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1299,1376,1802,1828]" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,757,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1838,1864]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Host-plant.</emphasis>
It occurs on 
<taxonomicName authority="Dozy et Molk." authorityName="Dozy et Molk." box="[481,923,1838,1865]" class="Bryopsida" family="Grimmiaceae" genus="Racomitrium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Grimmiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="japonicum">
<emphasis box="[481,752,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Racomitrium japonicum</emphasis>
Dozy et Molk.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[937,1092,1838,1865]" class="Bryopsida" family="Grimmiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Grimmiales" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="family">Grimmiaceae</taxonomicName>
) in 
<collectingCountry box="[1135,1199,1839,1865]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Maehara, S." box="[1214,1381,1838,1864]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="57 - 64" refId="ref4127" refString="Maehara, S. (2014) [Tingidae from Tochigi-ken, Honshu, Japan]. Insekuto, 65 (1), 57 - 64. [in Japanese]" type="journal article" year="2014">Maehara 2014</bibRefCitation>
; personal observation). This species has been collected from unidentified mosses in 
<collectingCountry box="[1039,1173,1874,1900]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1268,1345,1874,1900]" name="Russia" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Russia</collectingCountry>
, and the 
<collectingCountry box="[151,228,1910,1936]" name="United States of America" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
(Drake &amp; Lattin 1963; 
<bibRefCitation author="Golub, V. B." box="[493,630,1910,1936]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="628 - 632" refId="ref3713" refString="Golub, V. B. (1973) On the taxonomy of the Palaearctic lacebugs of the genus Acalypta Westw. (Heteroptera, Tingidae). Entomologicheskoe Obozrenie, 52, 628 - 632. [in Russian, English summary]" type="journal article" year="1973">Golub 1973</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="179" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,757,2009]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1945,1972]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Biology.</emphasis>
It overwinters as nymphs in 
<collectingCountry box="[633,700,1947,1973]" name="Japan" pageId="1" pageNumber="179">Japan</collectingCountry>
; adults are observed from April to June (
<bibRefCitation author="Maehara, S." box="[1173,1343,1946,1972]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="57 - 64" refId="ref4127" refString="Maehara, S. (2014) [Tingidae from Tochigi-ken, Honshu, Japan]. Insekuto, 65 (1), 57 - 64. [in Japanese]" type="journal article" year="2014">Maehara 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Adults have been collected from May to September in other countries (Drake 1917; 
<bibRefCitation author="Golub, V. B." box="[1013,1149,1982,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="628 - 632" refId="ref3713" refString="Golub, V. B. (1973) On the taxonomy of the Palaearctic lacebugs of the genus Acalypta Westw. (Heteroptera, Tingidae). Entomologicheskoe Obozrenie, 52, 628 - 632. [in Russian, English summary]" type="journal article" year="1973">Golub 1973</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Golub, V. B." box="[1160,1219,1982,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="221 - 253" refId="ref3757" refString="Golub, V. B. (1977) Lacebugs (Heteroptera, Tingidae) of the Mongolian People's Republic. Nasekomye Mongolii, 5, 221 - 253. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="1977">1977</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Golub, V. B." box="[1230,1289,1982,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="163 - 170" refId="ref3873" refString="Golub, V. B. (1998) New and little known lacebugs of the genera Acalypta Westw. and Dictyonota Curt. from the East and Central Palaearctic (Heteroptera: Tingidae). Zoosystematica Rossica, 7, 163 - 170." type="journal article" year="1998">1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jing, X. L." box="[1301,1414,1982,2008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="179" pagination="395 - 403" refId="ref4090" refString="Jing, X. L. (1980) New species of Chinese Tingidae (Hemiptera, Heteroptera). Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica, 5, 395 - 403. [in Chinese, English summary]" type="journal article" year="1980">Jing 1980</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
